Linear regression modelling

This chapter includes the basics of linear regression modelling using a dataset of international survey results of Approaches to Learning.

More information on the data is found here: https://www.mv.helsinki.fi/home/kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-meta.txt

During this second week I have got familiar with the basics of linear regression and R tools/functions for linear regression modelling. Linear regression itself was not any new method for me but this was probably my first regression analysis I have done in R by myself. Plotting functions for graphical overview of the data were new for me, and they are quite useful! Also different plots for exploring the validity of regression models are something to remember.

In general, linear regression modelling seems to be quite straightforward at least with this kind of simple and tidy data.

Model 1

In this linear regression model the exam points are explained by three variables: attitude, points of Strategic approach and Surface approach.

The intercept refers the value of y when x = 0. When there are multiple explanatory variable, it is the mean value of response variable when all x = 0. The values below (Estimate) means the slopes of the each parallel fitted line for each explanatory variable. Values >0 refers positive relationship and <0 negative relationship. E.g. higher points in attitude increases the predicted amount of points in the exam. The asterisk (*) shows statistically significant (p< 0.05) relationships.

The residual standard error is the standard deviation of the residuals referring the distance between each observation and the fitted line.

Multiple R-squared and Adjusted R-squared are (multiple) correlation coefficients measuring the linear correlation between explanatory and dependent variables. The adjusted R-squared is a modified version of R-squared that adjusts for the number of predictors in a regression model.

R-squared means how much (a proportion) the explanatory variables in this model can explain the variance of the outcome variable, which is here the exam points. R-squared can range from 0 to 1. R-squared 1 means that 100 % of the variance seen in the outcome variable can be explained by the explanatory variables. Thus, in the model1 three explanatory variables explain app. 19 % of the total exam points.

However, in this model1 only attitude significantly correlated to the exam points so stra and surf are not very useful or give any additional value in the model.

Lets make a new model:

# 3.2 Explanatory variable: attitude (as it was only with a significant relationship)
my_model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = lrn14)
summary(my_model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = lrn14)
## 
## Residuals:

## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
##

## (Intercept) 11.63715    1.83035   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude     0.35255    0.05674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

Model 2

As the parameters in the model2 compared to the model 1 are quite similar, we can conclude that in both models attitude is the main explanatory variable predicting the exam points. However, it has only quite a minor role in the outcome (points) and the model is not very useful for prediction. There seems to be unknown variables that mostly effect the success in the exam.

The R-squared values are slightly lower in the models 2. This is due to the fact that adding a new predictor variable to the model the R-squared will increase even if the predictor variable isnt useful (ref: https://www.statology.org/multiple-r-vs-r-squared/).

# We can also plot the new model:
library(ggplot2)

#4 Produce the following diagnostic plots: Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage. Explain the assumptions of the model and interpret the validity of those assumptions based on the diagnostic plots

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(my_model2, which = c(1,2,5))

Interpretation of model validity

Linear regression modelling has four main assumptions:

  1. Linear relationship between predictors and outcome;
  2. Independence of residuals;
  3. Normal distribution of residuals;
  4. Equal variance of residuals.

Harrison & Pius, 2021. R for Health Data Science.

Residuals vs.Fitted plot is used to check the assumptions 1-2 and 4:
A horizontal line closed to 0 is an indicator of a linear relationship and the residuals do not show any fitted pattern. This seems to be fine in the model 2.

Q-Q Residuals to check the 3. assumption:
Residuals are normally distributed when all plots follow approximately the reference line. The model2 shows quite good but not optimal as there are some dispersion at the extreme ends.

Residuals vs.Leverage plot can show outliers or those values that have a strong influence in a regression model.
The model2 does not show clear outlying observations and there are no observations which remarkably exceed the Cooks distance (= observations with a high influence).

In summary, based on the results presented above it can be concluded that
- there is a linear and positive relationship between the attitude and the total points in an exam
- attitude explains app. 19 % of the variance in exam points, and
- the linear regression model (model2) is (technically) valid but not very useful in predicting exam points based on attitude.

Student alc -data contains joined data from two data sets from https://www.archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/320/student+performance

Data includes 370 observations and 35 variables including demographics, background variables, data on alcohol use, school grades and absences. The average amount of absences and failures at school and average school grades (G1, G2, G3) have been calculated based on the values in two original data sets. Averaged weekly alcohol use (alc_use) has been calculated based on total alcohol consumption during weekdays and weekend. High alcohol use means alc_use > 2 (ranked by 1 - very low to 5 - very high)).

As seen in the bar plots, the data consists of school, family, health and free time related data on boys and girls mostly 15-18 years old. There seems to a bit more girls (n=195) than boys (n=175) with the similar age distributions (expect of a couple of older boys).

The overview summary graph shows that there are unequal group sizes in many binomial variables. This should be consider in further analysis as logistic regression models using imbalanced data tend to be biased towards the majority class. Therefore, we might select the binomial variables with more equal group size, e.g.activities, sex, and paid. To note, minority of students belong to the high alcohol use (the outcome variable) -group: 21 % of girls and 40 % of boys.

This analysis aims to study relationships between high/low alcohol consumption and 1) sex 2) current health status (health) 3) quality of family relationships (famrel) and 4) final grade (G3)

I hypothesize that
1) boys use (slightly) more alcohol than girls
2) students who feels healthier (higher health) may consume less alcohol
3) students who are using more alcohol (high_use=TRUE) have more problems in their family relationships (lower famrel)
4) students using more alcohol have lower final grades.

In general, 30 % of students belongs to the high_use group. The mean final grade the quality of family relationships are a bit lower in the high users groups as expected. Contrary to hypothesis, the current health status seems to be better in the high users -group. This might be affected by confounding factors, such as attitudes (towards drinking) and age-related issues, relationships with friends and freetime activities. Additionally, adolescents may ignore the negative side effects of drinking.

There seems to be differences between boys and girls in most variables, so it is important to consider the sex as an explanatory variable.

The summary of distributions of the outcome (high_use) and explanatory variables shows that boys are more likely to consume more alcohol than girls as expected.

Final grade does not notably seem to differ in girls who drink more vs.less alcohol but boys consuming more alcohol have lower final grades (as expected). There are four boys in high user -group with very low grade (considered as outliers in the plot). However, distribution of the final grade is large also in other boys.

There are overall no big differences in the current health status based on the alcohol consumption. Boys have reported a slightly better health status compared to girls. Sex differences in health status could be explained by the fact that girls have more mental health problems in adolescence in general. Additionally, the box plot shows that distribution of health status is wider in girls, and girls consuming more alcohol have reported better health status compared to girls using less alcohol. Thus, the overall difference seen in the link between alcohol use and health is origin from the differences seen in girls specifically. To note, the middle line in the box plot refers the median and the box includes 50 % of observations. The summary tibble above includes mean values. Therefore, one could do opposite conclusions of sex differences in health if only look at the summary table.

The quality of family relationships seems to be a bit lower in those who drink more alcohol, as expected. There seems to be no sex differences. It can be speculated whether poor family relationships increase the tendency to use more alcohol or vice versa. Probably there are several factors affecting both issues.

There are statistically significant correlation between the final grade and health. As health does not show statistically significant relationship with high alcohol use, it could be removed from the analysis. However, lets not continue with all explanatory variables

library(tidyverse)

# logistic regression model 

m1 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + health + famrel + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# print out a summary of the model
summary(m1)

The model summary shows that sex, family relationship and final grade (G3) but not health status have statistically significant relationships with high alcohol use. Male sex has positive correlation and both family relationship and final grade have negative correlations with higher alcohol consumption. These results are in line with the plotting results. Sex seems to have strongest and also the most significant correlation while the final grade has only a minor effect (|Estimate| i.e.the slope is small).

# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m1) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)
CI <- confint(m1)
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
# print out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
cbind(OR, CI)
##                    OR       2.5 %      97.5 %
## (Intercept) 1.8271637 -0.77171869  1.98759217
## sexM        2.6155032  0.49274622  1.44214153
## health      1.0937962 -0.08103054  0.26449411
## famrel      0.7141815 -0.59110838 -0.08555812
## G3          0.9185904 -0.15727983 -0.01418937

Odds ratios (OR) above 1 indicates that the event (here high alcohol use) is more likely to occur when sex = Male or continuous predictor increases. So, boys are about 2.6-times likely to be high consumers than girls.

Family relationships and final grade have ORs < 0 meaning that high alcohol use is less likely to occur if these variables increase. For example, one unit increase in the quality of family relationship in the Likert scale decreases app. 30 % of the odds to high alcohol consumption.

As the odds for Health is close to 1, there is no real association between the health status in general and alcohol consumption.

Confidence interval 95 % means that the value of the odds ratio for the population is with 95 % confident within this range. For example for sex, (0.49274622, 1.44214153).

These results further support the previous results.

# Exploring the predictive performance of the model.

# Statistically significant explanatory variables: sex, famrel, final grade
library(dplyr)

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m1, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc' as a new variable
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# see the first ten original classes, predicted probabilities, and class predictions

  geom_point()

plot_m1

# Computing the total proportion of inaccurately classified individuals
# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.3027027

As already expected based on the cross-table, the total proportion of inaccurate predictions is quite big: 30 %. Most of students in high use -group have inaccurate prediction but the model can predict quite well and accurately those who are not in the high use group.

All assumptions, for example linearity of continuous variables to the response, for logistic regression were not explored and those can affect the model performance. In addition, final grade showed relationship with alcohol consumption only in boys. There might be some interaction between these explanatory variables that decrease the predictive performance of the model.

Boston data includes housing data in suburb of Boston. Data consists of 14 numerical variables and 506 observations.
- crim: per capita crime rate by town.
- zn: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
- indus: proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
- chas: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
- nox: nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).
- rm: average number of rooms per dwelling.
- age: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
- dis: weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
- rad: index of accessibility to radial highways.
- tax: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.
- ptratio: pupil-teacher ratio by town.
- black: 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.
- lstat: lower status of the population (percent).
- medv: median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  graphics::arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale =2.5)

The results of the LDA models shows that there are three linear discriminants in the model: LD1, LD2, and LD3. Each of these are a combination of variables that give the (three) best possible separation between groups. Proportion of trace is the percentage separation achieved by each discriminant function. Thus, the LD1 can separate different groups (or here crime classes) with over 90 % accuracy. To note, the separation percentages for LD2 and LD3 are low (only 1-5 %).

Rad shows the strongest (positive) relationship with the crime as the coefficient is around 3 in LD1. Additionally, nox and age seems to have positive relationship with the target crim.

To visually support this, the LDA plot shows the cluster of high crime group which is separating from the other classes in LD1 mainly due to the accessibility to radial highways (rad). There are also some med_high cases included in this cluster. The other cluster (for LD1) consists of three other groups: low, med_low and most med_high cases. Low group seems to separate from the med_high cases in LD2, mainly due to the zn (low), nox and medv (med_high) variables. Med_low cases seems to be between low and med_high cases.

The cross-tabulation of predicted and correct classed shows that the LDA model is predicting correctly the high class and also quite nicely the low class. For the middle classes there are increasing number of incorrect predictions but still most of the cases are correctly predicted. Thus, the prediction performance of the LDA model is good and excellent for the high class.
